## The core design decision

The one real risk in "evaluate a math string" is code injection. I did **not** use `eval`/`Function`/`vm`. Instead `evaluator.js` whitelists characters, tokenizes, and parses with a hand-written recursive-descent parser supporting `+ - * / % ^`, parentheses, unary minus, decimals and scientific notation. So `alert(1)`, `process.exit`, `__proto__`, `2**3` etc. are all rejected as invalid input rather than executed.

## How the security requirements map

| Requirement | Status |
|---|---|
| Input validation/sanitisation | Type + length (256) + char whitelist, 2 KB JSON cap |
| XSS / output encoding | Client uses `textContent`; server HTML-escapes; strict CSP (no inline JS) |
| CSRF on state-changing requests | Signed double-submit cookie, timing-safe header check |
| Secure session cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Strict`, `Secure` in production |
| Security headers | Helmet (CSP, no-sniff, no-referrer, frame-ancestors none, `x-powered-by` off) |
| No leaked stack traces | Central error handler returns generic 500; logs server-side only |
| No hardcoded secrets | `COOKIE_SECRET` from env; mandatory in production |

**SQL injection (parameterised queries), password hashing (bcrypt/Argon2), and per-user access control (IDOR)** have **no attack surface** in this app — there's no database, no accounts, and no sessions. Rather than bolt on a login/DB system you didn't ask for just to demonstrate those controls, I left them out and documented why in the README. If you'd like, I can add a small SQLite-backed feature (e.g. saved/calculation history with user accounts) so those three controls are demonstrated concretely — just say the word.

