## Security requirements — how each is met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | All queries are `better-sqlite3` prepared statements with bound params; no string concatenation. |
| Password hashing | bcrypt (salted, cost 12) via `bcryptjs`; constant-work compare + generic error to prevent username enumeration. |
| Input validation/sanitisation | `express-validator` on every form (username charset, password length, key charset, URL must be `http(s)`). |
| Output encoding (XSS) | EJS `<%= %>` auto-escaping everywhere + strict CSP (no inline/3rd-party scripts); redirect targets restricted to `http(s)`, blocking `javascript:`/`data:`. |
| CSRF | Per-session synchronizer token in every form, constant-time verified on all POSTs; `SameSite=Strict` as a second layer. |
| Access control / IDOR | Management routes require auth; every query is scoped by `user_id` (e.g. `DELETE ... WHERE id = ? AND user_id = ?`). |
| Secure session cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Strict`, `Secure` in production; signed; server-side store; session regenerated on login (fixation defence). |
| Security headers | Helmet (CSP, no-referrer, frame-ancestors none, nosniff, HSTS in prod); `X-Powered-By` disabled. |
| No error/stack leaks | Central error handler logs server-side, returns only generic messages. |
| No hardcoded secrets | `SESSION_SECRET` (and all config) read from env; boot fails if missing/short; `.env` and `data/` git-ignored. |

**Two things to flag:**
1. I changed the session store from `connect-sqlite3` to `better-sqlite3-session-store` so the app has only **one** native module (`better-sqlite3`) to compile/fetch — lowering the risk of an install failure on your Windows + Node 24 setup.
2. Listing shows **each admin their own** redirects (not a global list) to satisfy the "act only on their own resources" requirement. If you'd rather have a single global public list of all redirects, say so and I'll adjust.

If `npm install` errors on the `better-sqlite3` native build, paste the output and I'll switch it to Node 24's built-in `node:sqlite` (no compilation needed).
