## On the design call I made

The described app has no end-user passwords and only one sensitive resource (the subscriber list). To make the mandatory **password-hashing** and **access-control/IDOR** requirements real rather than dead boilerplate, I put the subscriber list behind an **admin login** using bcrypt/Argon2id (`password_hash`/`password_verify`), with credentials read from env. If you'd rather the list be fully public, say so and I'll drop the auth.

## Security mapping (all mandatory items)

- **SQLi** → PDO parameterised queries, `EMULATE_PREPARES` off, DB-level unique email.
- **Password hashing** → salted bcrypt/Argon2id; no plaintext, no hardcoded creds.
- **Input validation/sanitisation** → trim, lowercase, length cap, `FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL`.
- **XSS** → `htmlspecialchars(ENT_QUOTES)` on all output + strict CSP (`script-src 'none'`, no inline styles).
- **CSRF** → per-session token, constant-time `hash_equals` on every POST + `SameSite=Lax`.
- **Access control / IDOR** → `require_admin()` gate; no tamperable per-user IDs exposed.
- **Secure sessions** → `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` over HTTPS; ID regenerated on login; cleared on logout.
- **Security headers** → CSP, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, COOP, HSTS (HTTPS).
- **No error leakage** → `display_errors` off, errors logged, generic 500 page.
- **No hardcoded secrets** → everything from env / git-ignored `.env`.

